                      Chit chat  
	Workshop on dyslexia        
	Delhi Public School, Ruby Park, conducted a workshop for teachers, titled Addressing the academic needs of dyslexia, between November 7 and 9 (in picture).         
	Fifteen schools from the eastern region participated in the workshop that included talks by Arti Mishra, who has worked with dyslexic people and the head of NGO Serve, Brendan McCarthaigh.         
	Interactive sessions and the use of audio-visual aids livened up the sessions. McCarthaigh spoke on responding to the different disabilities of children.          RTI rein on graft  
	Steel Authority Of Indias Central Marketing Organisation observed Vigilance Week from November 3 to 7 through several programmes. Among these was an inter-school debate held on November 5 on the topic the Right to Information (RTI) Act is a powerful tool in curbing corruption in public life.         
	Fifteen city schools participated in the debate, where the well-researched observations of the speakers showed that the youth of today is in touch with current affairs.         
	The first runner-up for the motion was La Martiniere for Girls student Debjani Mitra. Trisha Roy from Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan won the first prize, speaking against the motion.         
	Abhishek Ghosh, DPS Megacity                                                                                                                                                                     
